,"id":"38756"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87502"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted with a two day history of right upper quadrant pain and on the basis of the history is thought most likely to have acute cholecystitis. On physical examination a Murphy sign is demonstrated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this sign?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A palpable gallbladder in association with jaundice","Tenderness in the right upper quadrant","Inspiratory arrest during palpation under the right costal margin","Increased tenderness in the right upper quadrant, worsened by expiration","Tenderness in the right upper quadrant, exacerbated by inspiration"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe original description of the sign described by Murphy was applied to the situation where the \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdomen was soft, with no apparent tenderness\u003C/strong\u003E. The technique used was to try elicit localised tenderness, with the examiner hooking their fingers under the right costal margin and asking the patient to take some deep breaths in and out. When the gallbladder was pushed down by the contracting diaphragm, there would be a sudden interruption of inspiration as the inflamed organ came into contact with the indented parietal peritoneum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuch subtleties have now been lost and today\u0027s generation talk about \u0027a positive Murphys\u0027 when they mean that the patient has right upper quadrant tenderness that is readily apparent, without any extra measures being taken to elicit it. The meaning of many things change with time... The practicalities of trying to localise abdominal tenderness - any tenderness - is an increasing challenge with many of today\u0027s patients have a generous covering of adipose tissue masking much of what goes on underneath. In reality, if a patient is thought to have acute cholecystitis, an ultrasound will promptly be arranged to look for the presence of gallstones and thickening (acute inflammation) of the gallbladder wall. As in so many areas of medicine, investigations are replacing the art of history-taking and physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Murphy\u0027s sign was originally used to describe the observation of interruption of inspiration caused by the examiner\u0027s fingers gently pushing under the right costal margin in a patient with a suspected inflamed gallbladder."],"references":["Jeans PL, Murphy\u0027s sign. MJA 2017;206:116-17. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28208037/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71717"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-28T08:55:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T08:56:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1833"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87502"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":